1
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:32,672
<i>Here, Charlie. More fortune cookies.</i>

2
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:34,512
<i>- Good luck!</i>
<i>- Thanks! What?</i>

3
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:39,230
<i>Next week, we'll be selling</i>
<i>Sanyo remote control VCRs for $299!</i>

4
00:01:39,320 --> 00:01:41,788
- Look, it's Dad!
<i>- Oh, no! I'll go broke!</i>

5
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,028
<i>To give away Mitsubishi</i>
<i>giant-screen television sets for $1,299!</i>

6
00:01:47,200 --> 00:01:48,792
<i>Oh, no!</i>

7
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:53,908
<i>We won't be undersold on microwaves,</i>
<i>videorecorders, ovens...</i>

8
00:01:54,080 --> 00:01:57,277
- Mom, you're not looking.
- Please turn that off.

9
00:01:57,800 --> 00:02:00,155
Mom, when are you going to stop
being mad at Dad?

10
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:02,674
I mean, how do you think
that makes me feel?

11
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:05,752
I have certain unresolved feelings
about your father.

12
00:02:06,120 --> 00:02:07,519
I don't trust him.

13
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:11,437
- And I hate those commercials.
- All right, forget it.

14
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:13,590
We don't have time
for another heart-to-heart.

15
00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:15,352
Come on. You have to get dressed.

16
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:22,356
- I want you to understand it's insulting...
- Watch your hair.

17
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,278
...for him to go from me to that bimbo.
Do you think he really loves Janet?

18
00:02:28,040 --> 00:02:30,270
Maybe he's just smashed
too many fortune cookies!

19
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:33,238
Mom, give me a break!
He's missing the reunion because of you.

20
00:02:33,320 --> 00:02:35,038
You know he's dying to go.

21
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:38,280
At least we won't both have
a miserable time.

22
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:42,119
Let me see.

23
00:02:42,520 --> 00:02:44,158
What do you think?

24
00:02:44,440 --> 00:02:46,271
You are a very hip chick!

25
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:49,917
God, you look like you've stepped
right out of <i>Life</i> magazine!

26
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:51,235
I don't know.

27
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:53,788
What if nobody else there
is dressed like this?

28
00:02:53,880 --> 00:02:54,915
So?

29
00:02:55,720 --> 00:02:57,392
- I don't think I wanna go.
- Mom.

30
00:02:57,480 --> 00:03:00,995
Everybody's just gonna say,
"Well, hey, where's Crazy Charlie?"

31
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:04,320
Lots of people are separated and divorced.

32
00:03:05,720 --> 00:03:07,950
Not from the guy
with the lowest prices in town.

33
00:03:09,440 --> 00:03:11,954
I feel ridiculous in this dress!
I'd like to change.

34
00:03:12,040 --> 00:03:14,110
Why are you so nervous?
What's the matter?

35
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:16,350
Reunions do funny things
to people at this age.

36
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:18,590
- Hi, Peggy Sue! Beth!
- Hi.

37
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:20,789
Hi, Maddy.

38
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:22,389
How are you?

39
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:24,436
You two look
just like that soap commercial.

40
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:27,751
- "Which one's the mother?"
- "And which one's the daughter?"

41
00:03:29,160 --> 00:03:32,550
You took this seriously.
You're a real blast from the past!

42
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:34,638
It was Beth's idea.

43
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:38,036
I wish I had the nerve. And the figure.

44
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:40,953
- Hi.
- Hi! Peggy Sue Bodell?

45
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:43,076
- All right.
- Mom?

46
00:03:43,560 --> 00:03:45,312
Beth's boyfriend is with the band.

47
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:47,391
- Must run in the family.
- What does?

48
00:03:47,480 --> 00:03:50,631
You and your mother.
You both seem to fall for musicians.

49
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:02,159
Mom, look!

50
00:04:03,080 --> 00:04:04,354
Oh, God!

51
00:04:05,480 --> 00:04:08,631
It's okay. Come on. Look!

52
00:04:10,960 --> 00:04:13,793
Why don't you find a table?
We'll see you in a little while.

53
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:14,869
Sure.

54
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:19,592
God, Mom, that picture's great!
Come on, let's get a table.

55
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:35,192
- Is this good?
- Fine.

56
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:38,113
- I'll be right back. You be all right?
- Sure.

57
00:04:38,200 --> 00:04:41,272
<i>Thank you. We're gonna do</i>
<i>a little medley for you now.</i>

58
00:04:45,600 --> 00:04:49,115
- Come on, pose like your picture.
- What?

59
00:04:52,280 --> 00:04:54,271
Hi, do you like it?

60
00:04:54,360 --> 00:04:57,909
I figured as everyone has a gold Rolex,
I'd have one made in platinum.

61
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,560
- What a wonderful idea!
- How are you?

62
00:05:00,640 --> 00:05:02,790
I'm fine. How many children do you have?

63
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:05,235
- I don't have any.
- You don't? I thought you did.

64
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:07,436
- No. How many do you have?
- I have four.

65
00:05:07,520 --> 00:05:08,669
- Four?
- Four, yeah.

66
00:05:08,760 --> 00:05:10,034
I'm so happy for you.

67
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:12,156
- I love them so much.
- How's Peggy Sue doing?

68
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:14,151
She was a mess,
right after they separated.

69
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:17,198
But I think she's coming out of it.
Seems to be friendly now.

70
00:05:17,280 --> 00:05:18,474
I'm so glad.

71
00:05:19,240 --> 00:05:21,231
Sometimes it's easier when you hate them.

72
00:05:21,600 --> 00:05:24,672
- How about a little dance, princess?
- Walter!

73
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:27,716
- How are you?
- Good.

74
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:30,680
- Nice to see you. I'll see you later.
- Yeah.

75
00:05:31,600 --> 00:05:33,636
Aren't you Peggy Sue Kelcher?

76
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:38,475
I was once. Richard Norvik?

77
00:05:40,440 --> 00:05:42,192
I didn't recognise you!

78
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:45,158
You look terrific.
You look exactly the same.

79
00:05:45,240 --> 00:05:48,073
I feel ridiculous!
I only did this for tonight, you know.

80
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:50,071
- It's adorable.
- Thank you.

81
00:05:50,160 --> 00:05:52,879
Peggy Sue Kelcher, this is my wife, Sharon.

82
00:05:52,960 --> 00:05:56,669
- How nice to meet you. Why don't you sit?
- Thank you.

83
00:05:56,760 --> 00:05:59,479
But call me Peggy. Peggy Bodell now.

84
00:06:00,200 --> 00:06:02,270
So, where's Charlie?

85
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:07,191
I was in town about a year ago
and I turn on the television...

86
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:10,033
...and I see Crazy Charlie.

87
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:12,437
It really made me laugh.

88
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:15,270
Charlie won't be here tonight.

89
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:21,911
- We're getting divorced, actually.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

90
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:24,879
Mr. Norvik!

91
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:27,679
Richard. Doug Snell, Merrill Lynch.

92
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:32,514
I read about that Codex deal
in <i>Business Week.</i> Congratulations!

93
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:35,076
Thank you very much.

94
00:06:35,320 --> 00:06:39,393
Peggy, how are you? How's Charlie?
Hey, Terry!

95
00:06:39,640 --> 00:06:42,154
- Thank you, Doug, thank you very much.
- Call me.

96
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:45,756
Madeline Hutton and Arthur Nagle
were high school sweethearts.

97
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:49,037
Married right after graduation,
they're still together.

98
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:54,274
Maddy. Arthur. How does it feel
to have missed the sexual revolution?

99
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:56,955
What? What kind of question is that?

100
00:06:57,040 --> 00:06:59,838
That doesn't have anything to do
with the reunion, Delores!

101
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:01,148
Take it easy, kitten.

102
00:07:03,320 --> 00:07:06,756
- Welcome to the singles scene.
- I don't know how you do it.

103
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:09,908
I've never even dated anybody but Charlie.

104
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:12,312
It's not that bad, really.

105
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:16,439
You just have to think of men like houses,
and trade upward.

106
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:23,073
I always thought that you and Charlie
had a really great marriage.

107
00:07:23,760 --> 00:07:25,079
I think we did.

108
00:07:26,160 --> 00:07:27,752
We just got married too young...

109
00:07:27,840 --> 00:07:31,310
...and ended up blaming each other
for all the things we missed.

110
00:07:31,520 --> 00:07:35,354
So he started having affairs
and you started getting depressed?

111
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:40,518
You just should have left here years ago,
like I did.

112
00:07:40,840 --> 00:07:42,239
It's not so bad.

113
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:46,110
I've got two great kids.
I've got my own business.

114
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:52,033
Still, if I knew then what I know now...

115
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:55,635
...l'd do a lot of things differently.

116
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:58,879
Your damn computers
put me out of business.

117
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:00,115
You're right. He's drunk.

118
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:02,509
You're a billionaire
and I'm a goddamn failure.

119
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:05,037
No, the bakery's doing very well.

120
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:08,112
- Do you manage it?
- I own it.

121
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:10,352
I remember that dress.

122
00:08:12,920 --> 00:08:14,433
Rosalie?

123
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:19,237
Oh, no. I remember that locket, too.

124
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:23,673
You were so excited!
I think you showed it to the whole school.

125
00:08:23,760 --> 00:08:25,318
You have an incredible memory.

126
00:08:25,400 --> 00:08:28,358
- It's beautiful. Does it open?
- Yes.

127
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:33,117
- These are my children.
- They're so cute!

128
00:08:33,200 --> 00:08:35,236
Of course, they're not babies anymore!

129
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:38,039
But you were married
when you were three, right?

130
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:40,352
God bless you!

131
00:08:45,400 --> 00:08:47,630
The best thing about being a dentist.

132
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:49,758
Pure pharmaceutical grade.

133
00:08:50,160 --> 00:08:53,232
A couple of lines of this,
I could drill my own teeth.

134
00:08:58,120 --> 00:08:59,155
Hi.

135
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:02,069
Hi.

136
00:09:09,080 --> 00:09:12,117
- Who's the guy with the eyes?
- Michael Fitzsimmons.

137
00:09:12,600 --> 00:09:14,909
I used to have
such a crush on him in school.

138
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,672
- Peggy.
- Hi!

139
00:09:16,800 --> 00:09:19,075
God, that Walter Getz can still dance!

140
00:09:20,440 --> 00:09:24,228
Your first boyfriend!
Come on, tell me. Any sparks left?

141
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:25,719
Well, who knows?

142
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:28,792
I mean, remember,
whatever Walter wants...

143
00:09:28,880 --> 00:09:30,916
...Walter gets!

144
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:35,792
I'm sorry. Sharon Norvik.

145
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:40,352
This is Carol Heath and Maddy Nagle,
my oldest and my dearest friends.

146
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:42,829
- Nice to meet you.
- Sharon is married to Richard.

147
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:44,478
- Lucky lady!
- Thank you.

148
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:46,869
Michael Fitzsimmons. Is he here?

149
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:50,358
No. No, I asked Rosalie.
She couldn't track him down.

150
00:09:50,440 --> 00:09:53,273
- That's too bad.
- He must have been quite a guy.

151
00:09:53,360 --> 00:09:54,270
Yeah.

152
00:09:55,280 --> 00:09:59,273
You know, he is the only boy in high school
I wish I'd gone to bed with!

153
00:09:59,360 --> 00:10:00,634
Only one?

154
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:03,750
Well, besides Charlie.

155
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:11,231
I hope the sales of your book go very well.

156
00:10:11,320 --> 00:10:13,390
Anything anecdotal
you'd like to leave us with?

157
00:10:13,480 --> 00:10:15,516
Yeah, every dog has its day.

158
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:16,749
Meaning what?

159
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:20,992
Peggy, would you please rescue Richard?
Ask him to dance.

160
00:10:21,080 --> 00:10:23,674
Richard. Would you like to dance?

161
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:26,228
Of course I would.
So, are we through now?

162
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:27,435
- No.
- Good.

163
00:10:28,680 --> 00:10:30,750
From snivelling runt
to pompous ass in 25 years.

164
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:32,558
That's quite an accomplishment.

165
00:10:39,280 --> 00:10:41,510
I really cannot get over this.

166
00:10:41,880 --> 00:10:45,429
The only time people like Delores Dodge
used to pay any attention to me...

167
00:10:45,520 --> 00:10:48,398
...was to laugh at me or insult me.

168
00:10:48,480 --> 00:10:50,311
- You know that guy Doug Snell?
- Yeah.

169
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:52,789
He shook my hand
when we walked in here?

170
00:10:52,880 --> 00:10:54,996
He used to call me, "Four-eyed worm."

171
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:58,072
You showed them all.

172
00:10:58,160 --> 00:11:00,833
You're rich and famous and successful...

173
00:11:02,200 --> 00:11:04,156
...and you have a beautiful wife.

174
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:07,915
You were always friendly to me.
I appreciated that.

175
00:11:28,840 --> 00:11:31,718
It's Crazy Charlie, the appliance king!

176
00:11:31,960 --> 00:11:33,712
Hey, Charlie!

177
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:38,592
Look at you! You're putting on
a little weight, man!

178
00:11:38,840 --> 00:11:40,796
You look great. Great.

179
00:11:41,360 --> 00:11:45,672
So, this is the reunion? It's wonderful.

180
00:11:45,760 --> 00:11:46,988
Like, wonderful!

181
00:11:47,080 --> 00:11:50,152
Are you and Peggy still talking?
I mean, is it amicable?

182
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:52,356
She hasn't changed at all, Charlie.

183
00:11:52,520 --> 00:11:55,512
- Your daughter's a real doll.
- "Why, I oughta<i>...</i>"

184
00:12:18,680 --> 00:12:19,669
<i>Hello.</i>

185
00:12:22,520 --> 00:12:24,272
Hello!

186
00:12:24,920 --> 00:12:29,198
<i>Can I have your attention, please?</i>
<i>Listen up! Can I have your attention?</i>

187
00:12:29,360 --> 00:12:31,874
<i>I know everybody's having a great time...</i>

188
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,198
<i>... but now, you have to get ready for</i>
<i>that moment you've all been waiting for.</i>

189
00:12:39,640 --> 00:12:41,392
Dad? Hi.

190
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:48,395
<i>The Reunion Committee has selected</i>
<i>a king and a queen.</i>

191
00:12:55,880 --> 00:12:57,233
<i>Let's get back to business.</i>

192
00:12:57,320 --> 00:13:00,312
<i>The Reunion Committee</i>
<i>has given this a lot of thought...</i>

193
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:04,439
<i>... and decided on two people</i>
<i>who best represent the spirit...</i>

194
00:13:04,520 --> 00:13:07,353
<i>... of Buchanan High's Class of '60!</i>

195
00:13:08,040 --> 00:13:09,519
What are you doing?

196
00:13:09,600 --> 00:13:12,592
<i>The king is someone who,</i>
<i>in more ways than one...</i>

197
00:13:12,680 --> 00:13:15,638
<i>... has come a long way since he left here...</i>

198
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:18,871
<i>... and we are especially proud</i>
<i>to welcome him back.</i>

199
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:22,033
<i>Richard Norvik!</i>
<i>Come on up here, King Richard!</i>

200
00:13:37,720 --> 00:13:39,756
I demand a recount!

201
00:13:42,920 --> 00:13:44,433
<i>That's gotta be Getz!</i>

202
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:47,516
<i>First you gotta learn how to count.</i>

203
00:13:50,040 --> 00:13:52,190
Hold me back!

204
00:13:54,520 --> 00:13:56,636
<i>Well, I just want to say thank you.</i>

205
00:13:57,280 --> 00:14:01,751
<i>Sharon and I feel real welcome.</i>
<i>We're having a great time.</i>

206
00:14:02,480 --> 00:14:05,119
<i>Boy, our high school</i>
<i>looks really good from up here.</i>

207
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:09,113
<i>And I just wanna say, it's good to be back.</i>
<i>Thanks a lot.</i>

208
00:14:16,440 --> 00:14:20,115
<i>- Now, every king deserves a queen.</i>
- Over here!

209
00:14:20,640 --> 00:14:22,312
<i>Not you, Getz!</i>

210
00:14:22,880 --> 00:14:24,279
<i>Life of the party!</i>

211
00:14:25,040 --> 00:14:27,031
<i>But when we sent out the invitations...</i>

212
00:14:27,120 --> 00:14:30,237
<i>... we didn't mention anything about</i>
<i>this being a costume party...</i>

213
00:14:30,320 --> 00:14:31,958
<i>... and perhaps we should've...</i>

214
00:14:32,040 --> 00:14:34,838
<i>... because just looking at her</i>
<i>brings it all back!</i>

215
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:37,559
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
<i>I give you our queen...</i>

216
00:14:37,640 --> 00:14:41,758
<i>... Peggy Sue Kelcher Bodell!</i>
<i>Come on up here, Peggy Sue!</i>

217
00:14:42,320 --> 00:14:44,550
I can't. I can't do it.

218
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:46,113
Yes, you can.

219
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:50,757
Go on, you can do it. Go on.
You can do it.

220
00:15:17,520 --> 00:15:18,839
Congratulations.

221
00:15:27,280 --> 00:15:29,555
<i>Thank you, thank you very much.</i>

222
00:16:09,120 --> 00:16:10,189
Mom!

223
00:16:33,320 --> 00:16:35,550
Now, hold your arm up.

224
00:16:36,720 --> 00:16:38,711
Would you like your Twinkie now?

225
00:16:53,560 --> 00:16:54,709
Charlie?

226
00:16:57,040 --> 00:16:59,031
I want to suck your blood!

227
00:17:00,360 --> 00:17:02,476
I also want to suck your Twinkie!

228
00:17:02,960 --> 00:17:06,191
- Am I dead?
- No. You are the undead.

229
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:11,035
Let's have it. You hate them, anyway.

230
00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:14,358
Young man! You stop that!

231
00:17:14,520 --> 00:17:18,399
Hey, I just made a deposit in your bank.
Now I want to make a withdrawal.

232
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:20,755
I think it's time for your next class.

233
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:24,795
- Go on! All of you!
- I'm a little worried about the side effects.

234
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:28,476
Now, you lie back down.

235
00:17:31,880 --> 00:17:33,199
What am I doing here?

236
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:36,352
You passed out for a minute, that's all.
Nothing to worry about.

237
00:17:36,440 --> 00:17:40,877
- But how did I get here?
- Why don't you let your friends help you?

238
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:45,516
Take her into the washroom
and splash some cold water on her face...

239
00:17:45,600 --> 00:17:48,319
...and that should perk her up.
- Yes, ma'am.

240
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:49,879
How are you doing?

241
00:17:53,600 --> 00:17:56,672
Blood drive? 1960?

242
00:18:00,840 --> 00:18:01,909
Wanna smoke?

243
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:04,389
No, Carol. That's the worst thing for her.

244
00:18:04,480 --> 00:18:06,198
I gave them up years ago.

245
00:18:08,600 --> 00:18:11,194
- Where is it?
- Where's what?

246
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:15,430
Maddy, what did you do to your hair?

247
00:18:17,280 --> 00:18:19,316
I'm taking you back to the nurse.

248
00:18:23,800 --> 00:18:27,270
- Delores, why aren't you giving blood?
- I can't. I'm too anaemic.

249
00:18:27,360 --> 00:18:29,555
Maybe you should drink
some of that nail polish.

250
00:18:29,640 --> 00:18:30,755
It might give you strength.

251
00:18:30,840 --> 00:18:33,149
Why don't you come back
and show me how?

252
00:18:40,560 --> 00:18:42,278
We're going to take you home now.

253
00:18:42,360 --> 00:18:45,352
That's okay.
I'm sure I can remember the way.

254
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:53,353
Steady now.

255
00:18:55,240 --> 00:18:56,958
People get weak when they give blood.

256
00:19:19,760 --> 00:19:21,591
<i>It's wonderful Spring Radio.</i>

257
00:19:21,680 --> 00:19:25,958
<i>At 1280 on your AM dial,</i>
<i>here's more from our golden survey.</i>

258
00:19:28,720 --> 00:19:32,076
<i>And now from The Champs,</i>
<i>let's party with a little</i> Tequila.

259
00:19:56,880 --> 00:20:00,395
- I'll call you later.
- Yes! Let's keep in touch.

260
00:20:36,160 --> 00:20:37,479
Who is it?

261
00:20:38,280 --> 00:20:41,113
Peggy. Peggy Sue.

262
00:20:41,640 --> 00:20:44,473
Come on in. I left the door open for you.

263
00:20:59,400 --> 00:21:01,994
The nurse called
and said you'd be coming home.

264
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:03,513
I have a note.

265
00:21:05,560 --> 00:21:09,314
- How do you feel?
- I was excused.

266
00:21:09,840 --> 00:21:12,593
Why don't you go upstairs
and lie down for a while?

267
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:15,917
Oh, Mom!

268
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:21,508
Chanel No. 5.
It always reminds me of home.

269
00:21:21,600 --> 00:21:24,034
Of course, dear. You're home now.

270
00:21:26,240 --> 00:21:29,755
- You sure you're going to be all right?
- Yeah.

271
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:22,991
What is going on?

272
00:22:28,600 --> 00:22:29,589
Nancy?

273
00:22:30,640 --> 00:22:32,551
It's Nancy!

274
00:22:35,360 --> 00:22:37,715
My baby sister!

275
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:47,514
- I'm so happy to see you!
- What are you doing?

276
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:51,430
Mom said you were sick.
You're never happy to see me.

277
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:54,478
I'm sorry! I'm sorry about that.

278
00:22:55,320 --> 00:22:57,151
I want us to be closer.

279
00:22:57,360 --> 00:23:00,477
I have too many unresolved relationships
in my life.

280
00:23:01,120 --> 00:23:03,998
Teenagers are weird.
And you're the weirdest.

281
00:23:07,320 --> 00:23:09,470
You wanna play a game?

282
00:23:09,640 --> 00:23:10,993
Come here.

283
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:15,160
How about Monopoly?

284
00:23:15,240 --> 00:23:19,791
Or Parcheesi. Or Chutes and Ladders?

285
00:23:20,720 --> 00:23:22,915
<i>I have a question.</i>
<i>Let me turn the tables on you.</i>

286
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:24,479
<i>Maybe you, down here, don't know.</i>

287
00:23:24,560 --> 00:23:28,235
<i>Is there anybody in the house knows</i>
<i>where Dion and the Belmonts are?</i>

288
00:23:29,560 --> 00:23:32,518
I don't believe it.
Look at that man. He never ages.

289
00:23:32,760 --> 00:23:34,796
Isn't Kenny Rossi dreamy?

290
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:38,756
I wish he'd break up with Arlene.
She thinks she's so great.

291
00:23:39,640 --> 00:23:42,757
- Don't eat any of the red ones.
- Why not?

292
00:23:42,840 --> 00:23:47,834
They're bad for you.
They give you red lips.

293
00:24:09,800 --> 00:24:12,314
What the hell? I'm probably dead anyway.

294
00:24:12,520 --> 00:24:15,751
Peggy Sue, get in here!
Dion's almost over.

295
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:28,515
I left your laundry on your beds, girls.
Don't forget to put it away, okay?

296
00:24:28,600 --> 00:24:29,828
What's for dinner?

297
00:24:29,920 --> 00:24:31,990
Creamed chipped beef on toast
with rutabagas.

298
00:24:32,080 --> 00:24:33,798
Your father's favourite.

299
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:35,996
Not again!

300
00:24:36,520 --> 00:24:39,159
Evelyn! Girls?
What is this out on the street?

301
00:24:39,760 --> 00:24:41,830
Come and take a look!
Who left this out here?

302
00:24:41,920 --> 00:24:44,832
- What is it, dear?
- Come on out and see for yourself!

303
00:24:44,920 --> 00:24:46,273
Don't yell. Stop shouting.

304
00:24:50,560 --> 00:24:52,073
It's cool!

305
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:57,435
- Dad!
- Wait until I tell Diane.

306
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:00,080
She's always bragging
about her dad's Cadillac.

307
00:25:00,160 --> 00:25:01,912
What do you think, Peggy Sue?

308
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:06,994
Oh, Dad! You were always doing
stuff like that! It's funny.

309
00:25:07,240 --> 00:25:11,552
It's really funny. You bought an Edsel.

310
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:16,035
Young lady, what's the matter with you?

311
00:25:16,960 --> 00:25:18,154
Are you drunk?

312
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:23,716
Just a little. I had a tough day.

313
00:25:27,240 --> 00:25:29,435
No, don't wear it out, Nancy!

314
00:25:30,400 --> 00:25:33,551
We can't afford a new car.
Do we have to take it back?

315
00:25:34,240 --> 00:25:37,550
I fail to see the humour of this!
Go to your room, you're grounded!

316
00:25:37,640 --> 00:25:40,234
- Grounded?
- Put that down!

317
00:25:40,760 --> 00:25:43,433
That's the story of my life! I'm an adult.

318
00:25:43,560 --> 00:25:46,074
I'm going to go to Liverpool
and discover The Beatles.

319
00:25:46,160 --> 00:25:48,993
Jack, take it easy!
She gave blood at school today.

320
00:25:49,080 --> 00:25:52,993
- She's a little lightheaded.
- This is not giving blood! This is drunk!

321
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:56,838
Dad, I never knew you had
a sense of humour.

322
00:25:56,960 --> 00:25:59,599
- Evelyn, put her to bed!
- Come on, Mom!

323
00:25:59,720 --> 00:26:01,915
You're making a mountain
out of a molehill.

324
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:03,513
A tempest in a teapot!

325
00:26:05,480 --> 00:26:07,038
My little baby.

326
00:26:13,400 --> 00:26:15,311
Don't try to grow up so fast.

327
00:26:17,480 --> 00:26:19,789
Mom, I forgot you were ever this young.

328
00:26:20,880 --> 00:26:22,279
Sleep, baby.

329
00:26:46,920 --> 00:26:48,035
Good morning.

330
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:52,432
What happened to your hair, Peggy?
You have such a pretty face.

331
00:26:52,640 --> 00:26:55,871
- Why are you always trying to cover it up?
- I forgot.

332
00:26:56,440 --> 00:26:57,998
- 'Morning.
- 'Morning.

333
00:26:58,720 --> 00:26:59,789
Excuse me.

334
00:26:59,880 --> 00:27:02,838
Nancy, put your homework down
and sit down.

335
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:06,670
You're looking bright and chipper
this morning.

336
00:27:06,760 --> 00:27:10,070
I'm still here.
I thought I might as well enjoy myself.

337
00:27:10,160 --> 00:27:12,151
I think I'll go to school today.

338
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:15,917
You know, Dad, I'm sorry about yesterday.

339
00:27:16,880 --> 00:27:20,316
The Edsel is a classic.
Use it in the best of health.

340
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:21,719
Well, thank you.

341
00:27:21,920 --> 00:27:24,753
But don't ever let anything
like that happen again.

342
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:27,957
You're far too young
to start acquiring bad habits.

343
00:27:28,360 --> 00:27:30,430
I agree. You know, Mom and Dad...

344
00:27:31,320 --> 00:27:34,710
...you are the best parents
a girl could ever have.

345
00:27:35,640 --> 00:27:37,915
I'm really gonna try and behave myself.

346
00:27:38,200 --> 00:27:39,679
Sure you will!

347
00:27:41,960 --> 00:27:43,598
Come on, Momma, sit down.

348
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:46,033
You want me to sit?

349
00:27:46,520 --> 00:27:50,149
I mean, isn't this great?
Just all of us here together!

350
00:27:54,320 --> 00:27:56,788
Can I tell Charlie
Peggy Sue got drunk last night?

351
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:57,995
Young lady!

352
00:27:59,200 --> 00:28:02,112
I forgot about him. What am I gonna do?

353
00:28:02,280 --> 00:28:04,874
- Did you two have a fight?
- Sort of.

354
00:28:04,960 --> 00:28:06,757
- About what?
- House payments.

355
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:12,949
Baby!

356
00:28:14,120 --> 00:28:15,439
How do you feel?

357
00:28:16,240 --> 00:28:17,753
Pretty strange.

358
00:28:18,440 --> 00:28:21,113
Come on. Get in. I can take care of that.

359
00:28:25,240 --> 00:28:26,639
I have a headache.

360
00:28:28,520 --> 00:28:30,078
Headache?

361
00:28:35,840 --> 00:28:37,478
You drive like a maniac!

362
00:28:40,360 --> 00:28:42,271
It's not that I'm glad you were sick...

363
00:28:42,360 --> 00:28:46,114
...but it just gave me a chance
to do some thinking last night.

364
00:28:46,200 --> 00:28:50,512
- Yeah?
- Yeah. About what we said on Tuesday.

365
00:28:51,200 --> 00:28:53,316
I think it makes a lot of sense.

366
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:57,437
- Refresh my memory.
- How could you forget?

367
00:28:57,800 --> 00:29:00,951
We talk about seeing other people
and you forget.

368
00:29:02,800 --> 00:29:05,109
I must have blocked it out.

369
00:29:07,120 --> 00:29:10,430
Yeah. I guess I can understand that.

370
00:29:11,880 --> 00:29:15,270
But, please, don't start crying again.

371
00:29:25,200 --> 00:29:26,918
It's not gonna be forever.

372
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:32,279
I figure three years is long enough
for the music to pan out, which it will.

373
00:29:32,600 --> 00:29:33,919
I know it.

374
00:29:34,120 --> 00:29:36,793
So right after graduation we should...

375
00:29:36,880 --> 00:29:40,031
...one: Start to see other people
so that we can...

376
00:29:40,320 --> 00:29:42,880
...two: We can comparison-shop.

377
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:46,910
And then, three:
Settle down and get married.

378
00:29:49,560 --> 00:29:52,518
Why wait? Why not break up now?

379
00:29:53,800 --> 00:29:57,793
Because we got the prom coming up
and all these parties.

380
00:29:58,040 --> 00:30:01,715
- We don't want to upset our parents.
- They'll learn to live with it.

381
00:30:28,160 --> 00:30:29,229
Peggy Sue!

382
00:30:38,320 --> 00:30:41,312
Peggy Sue, come here.

383
00:30:55,160 --> 00:30:56,229
Peggy Sue.

384
00:30:56,880 --> 00:30:58,552
Did you study for the test?

385
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:02,315
- Test? There's a test?
- Yeah.

386
00:31:12,160 --> 00:31:14,196
All right, class. Time's up.

387
00:31:23,880 --> 00:31:26,314
And what's the meaning of this,
Peggy Sue?

388
00:31:27,120 --> 00:31:28,997
Mr. Snelgrove...

389
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:33,228
...I happen to know that in the future
I will have no use for algebra.

390
00:31:33,320 --> 00:31:35,117
And I speak from experience.

391
00:31:38,320 --> 00:31:39,912
- Who said that?
- I'm sorry.

392
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:40,989
Sit down!

393
00:31:41,160 --> 00:31:45,312
The result of his struggle is
that Santiago comes back with honour.

394
00:31:45,400 --> 00:31:47,789
Santiago comes back with nothing!

395
00:31:48,240 --> 00:31:50,037
There's no meat on the bone.

396
00:31:50,120 --> 00:31:52,793
It's Hemingway's ego
trying to defend itself again.

397
00:31:52,880 --> 00:31:55,075
Trying to prove he can still perform.

398
00:31:55,160 --> 00:31:58,709
What Hemingway's saying, Michael,
is that we are alone.

399
00:31:58,800 --> 00:32:01,439
That when we go out too far,
we're vulnerable.

400
00:32:01,800 --> 00:32:05,110
The irony that Santiago
is beaten by the sharks...

401
00:32:05,560 --> 00:32:07,676
...doesn't make him less of a hero.

402
00:32:07,800 --> 00:32:10,189
Who is the victim and who is the predator?

403
00:32:12,800 --> 00:32:14,870
We'll finish this discussion next week.

404
00:32:14,960 --> 00:32:18,873
And don't forget, first four chapters
of <i>The Great Gatsby</i> by Monday.

405
00:32:19,280 --> 00:32:20,759
Hope you enjoy it.

406
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:32,753
Why does your father take inventory
on Sunday nights?

407
00:32:32,840 --> 00:32:33,989
Hi, Peggy.

408
00:32:34,080 --> 00:32:37,311
It's poker night.
You always got out of it before.

409
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:40,949
I just gotta string him along for a while.
It's for his own good.

410
00:32:41,040 --> 00:32:44,350
You're not going into his business.
When are you gonna tell him?

411
00:32:44,440 --> 00:32:45,350
Soon.

412
00:32:48,720 --> 00:32:49,436
Walter!

413
00:32:49,520 --> 00:32:51,715
I can't tell everybody everything
all at once.

414
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:54,553
Strange rumours
are sweeping the school about you.

415
00:32:54,640 --> 00:32:55,959
Hi, Peggy.

416
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:57,155
What do you mean?

417
00:32:57,240 --> 00:33:01,631
- I hear you gave it to old Smellygrove.
- I was there! She told him off to his face!

418
00:33:01,720 --> 00:33:02,869
Attagirl, Peg!

419
00:33:02,960 --> 00:33:04,712
Arthur, please don't call me Peg.

420
00:33:04,800 --> 00:33:06,313
"Why, I oughta<i>...</i>"

421
00:33:09,080 --> 00:33:10,035
I don't get it.

422
00:33:10,120 --> 00:33:12,509
That's 'cause you're not
a total moron like they are.

423
00:33:12,600 --> 00:33:14,397
It's a stupid movie thing they started.

424
00:33:14,480 --> 00:33:16,391
That's enough outta you, little lady!

425
00:33:19,400 --> 00:33:20,913
"Why, I oughta<i>...</i>"

426
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:25,273
I'll be right back.

427
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:31,678
Hi, Richard.

428
00:33:32,880 --> 00:33:36,031
I wanted to congratulate you
on winning the math contest.

429
00:33:36,560 --> 00:33:38,232
It really wasn't that difficult.

430
00:33:38,320 --> 00:33:41,630
What are you doing?
You fishing for four-eyed worms?

431
00:33:42,320 --> 00:33:44,356
Get lost, you macho schmuck!

432
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:51,437
I wanted to talk to you.
It's really important.

433
00:33:52,040 --> 00:33:54,554
I'm not doing any tutoring this year.
I'm too busy.

434
00:33:54,640 --> 00:33:56,596
No, it's not about that.

435
00:33:56,840 --> 00:33:59,308
Would you meet me after school, please?

436
00:34:02,760 --> 00:34:05,558
All right. I'll be in the physics lab.

437
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:11,393
Make it 4:30.
I have to go to a Rocket Club meeting.

438
00:34:11,480 --> 00:34:12,310
Sure.

439
00:34:18,080 --> 00:34:19,832
She's not wasting any time.

440
00:34:19,960 --> 00:34:23,635
- Peggy Sue and Mr. Square Root.
- He's a nice guy. He's writing a book.

441
00:34:23,920 --> 00:34:26,753
A book? Excuse me for a second.

442
00:34:28,240 --> 00:34:29,958
Why is she punishing herself?

443
00:34:50,880 --> 00:34:54,589
Come on, Peggy Sue. Try it again.
You haven't been practising.

444
00:34:54,680 --> 00:34:55,829
Sorry.

445
00:34:55,920 --> 00:34:58,718
What a girl, what a twirl.
Peg "Leggy" Sue Kelcher.

446
00:34:58,800 --> 00:35:01,712
A brief but glorious career as a majorette.

447
00:35:04,200 --> 00:35:05,110
Baby!

448
00:35:08,760 --> 00:35:10,398
Looking good out there!

449
00:35:10,640 --> 00:35:11,595
Thanks.

450
00:35:16,400 --> 00:35:18,595
I love it when you twirl your baton.

451
00:35:22,080 --> 00:35:25,311
I noticed you were giving me
the silent treatment at lunch.

452
00:35:26,600 --> 00:35:28,158
I guess I deserved it.

453
00:35:28,280 --> 00:35:30,794
I've been thinking
about my three-year plan.

454
00:35:30,920 --> 00:35:34,708
I think it's totally unworkable.
I must have been delirious.

455
00:35:35,960 --> 00:35:38,235
I don't know.
I thought it made some sense.

456
00:35:38,320 --> 00:35:41,995
Well, in the abstract, maybe.
Get a good grip on yourself.

457
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:48,391
When I think about you going out
with other guys, I feel<i>...</i>

458
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:52,751
Rejected? Worthless? Miserable?

459
00:35:54,800 --> 00:35:55,915
Yeah.

460
00:35:57,400 --> 00:35:58,515
Good.

461
00:36:20,960 --> 00:36:22,234
Boy, that's some kite!

462
00:36:22,440 --> 00:36:24,829
I'm writing a book on kite construction.

463
00:36:25,400 --> 00:36:27,356
So what do you wanna talk about?

464
00:36:28,400 --> 00:36:30,516
I just wanted to ask you a question.

465
00:36:33,160 --> 00:36:35,720
Do you think time travel is possible?

466
00:36:38,160 --> 00:36:41,277
- Are you doing a science project?
- Sort of.

467
00:36:43,320 --> 00:36:46,312
Well, that's a very interesting question.

468
00:36:46,840 --> 00:36:48,114
Well, now, let's see.

469
00:36:48,200 --> 00:36:51,510
If we look at this
in a Newtonian framework...

470
00:36:52,080 --> 00:36:54,833
...the possibilities of time travel
were limited.

471
00:36:55,200 --> 00:36:59,079
With the advent of the relativity theory,
that's Einstein's relativity theory...

472
00:36:59,160 --> 00:37:02,152
...the idea of absolute time
cannot be reasonably affirmed.

473
00:37:03,440 --> 00:37:06,034
Well, then we have Richard's <i>burrito.</i>

474
00:37:07,360 --> 00:37:08,270
What's that?

475
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:11,591
That's my own theory,
based on a Mexican food called the <i>burrito.</i>

476
00:37:11,760 --> 00:37:15,435
- I had one at Disneyland.
- I know what a <i>burrito</i> is!

477
00:37:16,520 --> 00:37:19,478
You see, I think that time is like a <i>burrito...</i>

478
00:37:20,280 --> 00:37:23,397
...in the sense that one part of itself
will fold over...

479
00:37:23,480 --> 00:37:26,313
...and it will just touch the other part.

480
